\@doanenote {6}
macro:->Bayes'
theorem
follows
quickly
using
the
definition
of
conditional
probability.
We
have
$\Pr
(E|H)
=
\Pr
(H\land
E)/\Pr
(H)$.
Here
we
use
logical
conjunction
$\land
$
to
write
the
combined
event
$H$
and
$E$.
Hence,
$\Pr
(H\land
E)=\Pr
(E|H)\cdot
\Pr
(H)$.
It
follows
that
$\Pr
(H|E)
=
\Pr
(H
\land
E)/\Pr
(E)
=
\Pr
(E|H)\cdot
\Pr
(H)/\Pr
(E)$,
proving
Bayes'
theorem.

\@endanenote 
