\@doanenote {9}
macro:->The
language
of
'priors'
and
'posteriors'
is
standard
and
suggests
an
temporal
ordering.
However,
these
probabilities
are
all
assigned
at
the
same
time;
they
are
not
temporally
ordered.
Contrast
this
with
\textit
{Bayesian
updating}
which
is
the
controversial
epistemological
thesis
that
the
probability
of
$H$
\textit
{after}
considering
evidence
$E$
at
time
$t_2$
must
be
equivalent
to
the
condition
probability
$P(H|E)$
earlier
at
time
$t_1$.
\@endanenote 
\@doanenote {10}
macro:->To
derive
the
likelihood
ratio,
one
first
applies
Bayes'
theorem
to
both
$H$
and
$\neg
H$.
We
get
$\Pr
(H|E)
=
\Pr
(E|H)\cdot
\Pr
(H)/\Pr
(E)$
and
$\Pr
(\neg
H|E)
=
\Pr
(E|\neg
H)\cdot
\Pr
(\neg
H)/\Pr
(E)$.
Using
these,
we
find:
\par
\begin
{equation*}
\frac
{\Pr
(H|E)}{\Pr
(\neg
H|E)}
=
\frac
{\Pr
(E|H)\cdot
\Pr
(H)/\Pr
(E)}
{\Pr
(E|\neg
H)\cdot
\Pr
(\neg
H)/\Pr
(E)}
=
\frac
{\Pr
(E|H)\cdot
\Pr
(H)}
{\Pr
(E|\neg
H)\cdot
\Pr
(\neg
H)},
\end
{equation*}
\par
\noindent
proving
the
likelihood
ratio
formula.
\@endanenote 
